How Tokens & LLMs Are Attached to VR
In both options, the token (derived from VR inputs) is used to:

Drive LLM prompts – The token is embedded into a natural language query that asks the LLM to generate a suitable VR experience (e.g., “calm forest” or “exciting roller coaster”).

Select pre‑recorded VR scenes – The token can be hashed to an index in a library of 3D assets (e.g., using the token modulo number of scenes).

Modulate environmental parameters – Token value controls lighting, sound volume, or particle effects in real‑time via WebXR’s XRWebGLLayer.

Even without EEG, this creates a bio‑inspired adaptive VR system where the user’s behaviour (gaze, movement, speech) influences the virtual world almost as effectively as neural signals.

